            <tr>
              <td colspan="3">
                <p><b>Summary: Intervention and Options </b></p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td colspan="3" style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><b>RPC Opinion: </b></span><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">n/a</span></span></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td colspan="6">
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td colspan="5" style="background-color:#E0E0E0">
                <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Cost of Preferred (or more likely) Option </b></span></span><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">(in 2024 prices)</span></span></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Total Net Present Social Value</b></span></span></p>
              </td>
              <td style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Business Net Present Value</b></span></span></p>
              </td>
              <td colspan="2" style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Net cost to business per year </b></span></span></p>
              </td>
              <td style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle" rowspan="2">
                <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Business Impact Target Status</b></span></span></p>
                <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">Qualifying provision</span></span></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">£0m</span></span></p>
              </td>
              <td style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">-£101.3m</span></span></p>
              </td>
              <td colspan="2" style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">£11.8m</span></span></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td colspan="5">
                <p><span style="color:#000000"><b>What is the problem under consideration? Why is government action or intervention necessary?</b></span></p>
                <p>One of the reasons that the local authority planning application service is not consistently performing at the level it should be is a lack of resources because planning fees do not cover the cost of the service. This results in a funding shortfall for local authorities, of £362million in 2023-24, which local authorities have to fund from their general budgets. It is fair that service users bear a greater proportion of the costs of the service. Only Government has the power to increase planning fees. Fees will be increased where there is the greatest shortfall between the fee and cost of the service. In doing so, all local planning authorities will benefit from increased income and greater financial sustainability to support the delivery of an effective planning service.</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </hcontainer>
      <level>
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="7.18in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p><span style="color:#000000"><b>What are the policy objectives of the action or intervention and the intended effects?</b></span></p>
                <p>The policy objective is to improve the speed and quality of the planning application service provided by local planning authorities by generating a greater income for them through an increase in some of the fees with the greatest shortfall, which will enable them to secure more resources to deliver the service. It is fairer, as a greater proportion of the planning application service is funded, through fees, by those using the service. The intended effect can be measured by the local authority revenue and expenditure returns submitted by local authorities to Government<authorialNote marker="1"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing"><u>Local authority revenue expenditure and financing - GOV.UK</u></a><u> - </u><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</u></p></authorialNote>. Key indicators of success will be an improvement in the speed and quality of decision making<authorialNote marker="2"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/improving-planning-performance-criteria-for-designation"><u>Improving planning performance: criteria for designation - GOV.UK</u></a><u> - </u><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/improving-planning-performance-criteria-for-designation</u></p></authorialNote>. </p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="7.18in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p><span style="color:#000000"><b>What policy options have been considered, including any alternatives to regulation? Please justify preferred option (further details in Evidence Base)</b></span></p>
                <p>If Government did not increase these planning application fees (do nothing option), the planning service would not improve, because the shortfall between the fee and the cost of providing the service would remain. Delays in making decisions on planning applications will mean delays in the delivery of housing and other development needed for economic growth. Planning fees can only be increased through regulations. Our preferred option is to increase householder fees for extending properties from £258 to £528; to double fees for prior approval applications, from £120 / £125 / £258 to £240 / £250 / £516; to increase fees for discharge of conditions from £43 to £86 for householders and £145 to £298 for all other applications; and, to change the fees for applications to vary or remove conditions, reducing those for householders from £293 to £86, and increasing fees for other non-major applications from £293 to £586, and for majors from £293 to £2,000. The new fees will more closely represent the cost to local planning authorities of deciding these applications.  </p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="7.18in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <table uk:widths="4.34in 0.76in 0.6in 0.24in 0.44in 0.82in">
                  <tr>
                    <td colspan="2" style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0">Is this measure likely to impact on international trade and investment? </span></p>
                    </td>
                    <td colspan="4" style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0">No</span></p>
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0">Are any of these organisations in scope?</span></p>
                    </td>
                    <td style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Micro</b></span></span></p>
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">Yes</span></span></p>
                    </td>
                    <td style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Small</b></span></span></p>
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">Yes</span></span></p>
                    </td>
                    <td colspan="2" style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Medium</b></span></span></p>
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">Yes</span></span></p>
                    </td>
                    <td style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Large</b></span></span></p>
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">Yes</span></span></p>
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td colspan="2" style="background-color:#E0E0E0;vertical-align:middle">
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0">What is the CO</span><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0">2</span><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"> equivalent change in greenhouse gas emissions? </span><br /><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0">(Million tonnes CO</span><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0">2</span><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"> equivalent)</span><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0">  </span></p>
                    </td>
                    <td colspan="2" style="background-color:#E0E0E0">
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Traded:  </b></span></span><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000">N/A</span></span><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b> </b></span></span><br /><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>     </b></span></span></p>
                    </td>
                    <td colspan="2" style="background-color:#E0E0E0">
                      <p><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Non-traded:   </b></span></span><br /><span style="background-color:#E0E0E0"><span style="color:#000000"><b>N/A</b></span></span></p>
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                </table>
                <p><span style="color:#000000"><b>Will the policy be reviewed?  </b></span><span style="color:#000000">See ‘Monitoring and Evaluation’, page 8</span><span style="color:#000000">.</span><span style="color:#000000"><b> </b></span><span style="color:#000000"><b> If applicable, set review date:  </b></span><span style="color:#000000">N/A</span></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <content>
          <p><b><i>I have read the Impact Assessment and I am satisfied that, given the available evidence, it represents a reasonable view of the likely costs, benefits and impact of the leading options.</i></b></p>
          <table uk:widths="4.62in 2.46in">
